benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/admin/healthcheck - Put the host out of rotation

covered: DELETE Method - Valid Deletion: Success path returns 204 and updates host state (TC01, TC12).
DELETE Method - Non-Existent/Invalid State: 409 when host already out of rotation or none available (TC04, TC14).
DELETE Method - Concurrency: Concurrent DELETE requests handled; only one succeeds, others receive 409/204 as appropriate with timing checks (TC11).
DELETE Method - Soft-delete-like behavior: Host remains but flagged out of rotation and is verifiable via status query (TC12).
Error Handling: 500 internal error (TC06), 503 service unavailable (TC05), 405 method not allowed (TC07), 400 invalid/malicious body (TC09).
Authorization: 401 for missing or invalid credentials (TC02, TC03).
Security Hardening: Malicious headers are rejected with 400/401 (TC13).
Performance: Response-time expectations under normal and concurrent load (TC10, TC11).
Input Robustness: Extra query parameters do not break the operation (TC08).
gaps: Response headers/contract: Story states Produces: application/json, but tests do not assert Content-Type header semantics for 204 or errors; no checks for headers consistency.
Authorization breadth: No scenario for authenticated but insufficient privileges (403 Forbidden).
Idempotency (sequential): No explicit sequential repeat-call test verifying first 204 then subsequent 204/409 with no side effects (beyond concurrency).
Unsupported media type: No 415 test when a Content-Type is sent with an unsupported or non-empty body on DELETE.
Rate limiting/throttling: No scenario for burst traffic receiving 429 or equivalent handling (if applicable/policy-defined).
Spec alignment for extra query params: Behavior is assumed as OK (204) but not defined by story; lack of test asserting they are ignored vs rejected.
recommendations: Add header/contract checks: assert Content-Type behavior. For 204, confirm empty body and either absent Content-Type or agreed header; for error responses, assert application/json and error schema.
Add a 403 Forbidden scenario: valid auth with insufficient admin role should be denied.
Add a sequential idempotency scenario: call DELETE twice on the same host; expect first 204, second 409 or 204 per contract; verify host state remains out of rotation.
Add a 415 Unsupported Media Type test: send a payload with an unsupported Content-Type or any body when body is N/A; expect 415 or defined 400.
Consider a 429 rate limiting test under burst conditions if the platform enforces throttling.
Clarify and codify behavior for extraneous query parameters; update tests to either assert rejection (400) or explicit ignoring with no side effects.
